{
  "pattern": "glossary_reference",
  "title": "Eq. 10 Addendum: Variables",
  "entries": [
    {
      "term": "Overview",
      "body": [
        {
          "kind": "text",
          "value": "This addendum names the main variables and functions that appear in Eq. 10."
        },
        {
          "kind": "text",
          "value": "The equation balances the locked contribution and the drifting contribution to the order parameter r."
        }
      ],
      "referenceTitle": "Eq. 10",
      "reference": [
        {
          "kind": "topic_reference",
          "topicId": "kuramoto-eq10",
          "slot": "workspace"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "term": "r",
      "body": [
        {
          "kind": "math",
          "latex": "r",
          "displayMode": true
        },
        {
          "kind": "text",
          "value": "r is the magnitude of the collective order parameter. It measures how synchronized the oscillator population is."
        },
        {
          "kind": "text",
          "value": "Eq. 10 is self-consistent because r appears both on the left and inside the locking scale Kr on the right."
        }
      ],
      "referenceTitle": "Order Parameter",
      "reference": [
        {
          "kind": "mappings",
          "mappings": [
            {
              "kind": "latex",
              "value": "r",
              "hitBox": {
                "id": "order_parameter_r",
                "label": "order parameter",
                "sequence": "r",
                "category": "term",
                "latex": "r"
              }
            },
            {
              "kind": "text",
              "value": "\n"
            },
            {
              "kind": "latex",
              "value": "Kr",
              "hitBox": {
                "id": "locking_scale",
                "label": "locking scale",
                "sequence": "K r",
                "category": "term",
                "latex": "Kr"
              }
            }
          ]
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "term": "Psi and Theta",
      "body": [
        {
          "kind": "math",
          "latex": "\\psi,\\theta",
          "displayMode": true
        },
        {
          "kind": "text",
          "value": "Psi is the collective phase of the mean field. Theta is the phase of an individual oscillator."
        },
        {
          "kind": "text",
          "value": "The equation depends on the phase difference theta minus psi, not on the two phases separately."
        }
      ],
      "referenceTitle": "Phases",
      "reference": [
        {
          "kind": "mappings",
          "mappings": [
            {
              "kind": "latex",
              "value": "e^{i(\\theta-\\psi)}",
              "hitBox": {
                "id": "phase_factor",
                "label": "phase factor",
                "sequence": "e to the i times theta minus psi",
                "category": "term",
                "latex": "e^{i(\\theta-\\psi)}"
              }
            },
            {
              "kind": "text",
              "value": "\n"
            },
            {
              "kind": "latex",
              "value": "\\delta\\!\\left[\\theta-\\psi-\\sin^{-1}\\!\\left(\\frac{\\omega}{Kr}\\right)\\right]",
              "hitBox": {
                "id": "locked_constraint",
                "label": "locked delta constraint",
                "sequence": "delta of theta minus psi minus sine inverse of omega over K r",
                "category": "function",
                "latex": "\\delta\\!\\left[\\theta-\\psi-\\sin^{-1}\\!\\left(\\frac{\\omega}{Kr}\\right)\\right]"
              }
            }
          ]
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "term": "Omega",
      "body": [
        {
          "kind": "math",
          "latex": "\\omega",
          "displayMode": true
        },
        {
          "kind": "text",
          "value": "Omega is the natural frequency label of an oscillator. The population contains many oscillators with different omega values, so Eq. 10 integrates over omega."
        },
        {
          "kind": "text",
          "value": "Conditions involving omega decide whether an oscillator is locked or drifting."
        }
      ],
      "referenceTitle": "Natural Frequency",
      "reference": [
        {
          "kind": "mappings",
          "mappings": [
            {
              "kind": "latex",
              "value": "g(\\omega)",
              "hitBox": {
                "id": "frequency_density",
                "label": "frequency density",
                "sequence": "g of omega",
                "category": "function",
                "latex": "g(\\omega)"
              }
            },
            {
              "kind": "text",
              "value": "\n"
            },
            {
              "kind": "latex",
              "value": "|\\omega| > Kr",
              "hitBox": {
                "id": "drift_condition",
                "label": "drifting condition",
                "sequence": "absolute value of omega greater than K r",
                "category": "condition",
                "latex": "|\\omega| > Kr"
              }
            },
            {
              "kind": "text",
              "value": "\n"
            },
            {
              "kind": "latex",
              "value": "\\sin^{-1}\\!\\left(\\frac{\\omega}{Kr}\\right)",
              "hitBox": {
                "id": "omega_locked_offset",
                "label": "locked phase offset",
                "sequence": "sine inverse of omega over K r",
                "category": "term",
                "latex": "\\sin^{-1}\\!\\left(\\frac{\\omega}{Kr}\\right)"
              }
            }
          ]
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "term": "K",
      "body": [
        {
          "kind": "math",
          "latex": "K",
          "displayMode": true
        },
        {
          "kind": "text",
          "value": "K is the coupling strength between an oscillator and the collective mean field."
        },
        {
          "kind": "text",
          "value": "It appears through Kr, the effective locking scale. Larger K makes the locking condition easier to satisfy."
        },
        {
          "kind": "text",
          "value": "K and r play different roles. K is a fixed model parameter that sets how strongly oscillators pull on one another, while r is the emergent coherence level that tells how aligned the population already is."
        }
      ],
      "referenceTitle": "Coupling Strength",
      "reference": [
        {
          "kind": "mappings",
          "mappings": [
            {
              "kind": "latex",
              "value": "Kr",
              "hitBox": {
                "id": "locking_scale",
                "label": "locking scale",
                "sequence": "K r",
                "category": "term",
                "latex": "Kr"
              }
            },
            {
              "kind": "text",
              "value": "\n"
            },
            {
              "kind": "latex",
              "value": "\\frac{\\omega}{Kr}",
              "hitBox": {
                "id": "omega_over_locking_scale",
                "label": "frequency over locking scale",
                "sequence": "omega over K r",
                "category": "term",
                "latex": "\\frac{\\omega}{Kr}"
              }
            },
            {
              "kind": "text",
              "value": "\n"
            },
            {
              "kind": "latex",
              "value": "\\omega-Kr\\sin(\\theta-\\psi)",
              "hitBox": {
                "id": "drift_denominator_core",
                "label": "drift denominator core",
                "sequence": "omega minus K r sine of theta minus psi",
                "category": "term",
                "latex": "\\omega-Kr\\sin(\\theta-\\psi)"
              }
            }
          ]
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "term": "g(omega)",
      "body": [
        {
          "kind": "math",
          "latex": "g(\\omega)",
          "displayMode": true
        },
        {
          "kind": "text",
          "value": "g(omega) is the population frequency distribution. It tells how common each natural frequency is."
        },
        {
          "kind": "text",
          "value": "It is external population data, not a variable solved for by Eq. 10."
        }
      ],
      "referenceTitle": "Frequency Density",
      "reference": [
        {
          "kind": "mappings",
          "mappings": [
            {
              "kind": "latex",
              "value": "g(\\omega)",
              "hitBox": {
                "id": "frequency_density",
                "label": "frequency density",
                "sequence": "g of omega",
                "category": "function",
                "latex": "g(\\omega)"
              }
            }
          ]
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "term": "C",
      "body": [
        {
          "kind": "math",
          "latex": "C",
          "displayMode": true
        },
        {
          "kind": "text",
          "value": "C appears only in the drifting branch. It is the normalization factor that makes the drifting stationary density integrate correctly along a drift orbit."
        },
        {
          "kind": "text",
          "value": "So C is not a new order parameter. It is part of the density formula for oscillators that are not locked."
        }
      ],
      "referenceTitle": "Drift Normalization",
      "reference": [
        {
          "kind": "mappings",
          "mappings": [
            {
              "kind": "latex",
              "value": "\\frac{C g(\\omega)}{|\\omega-Kr\\sin(\\theta-\\psi)|}",
              "hitBox": {
                "id": "drift_density",
                "label": "drifting density weight",
                "sequence": "C g of omega over absolute value of omega minus K r sine of theta minus psi",
                "category": "term",
                "latex": "\\frac{C g(\\omega)}{|\\omega-Kr\\sin(\\theta-\\psi)|}"
              }
            }
          ]
        }
      ]
    }
  ]
}
